M|using-superpowers|These thoughts mean STOP—you're rationalizing:
M|using-superpowers|| Thought | Reality |
M|using-superpowers||---------|---------|
M|using-superpowers|| "This is just a simple question" | Questions are tasks. Check for skills. |
M|using-superpowers|| "I need more ctx first" | Skill check comes BEFORE clarifying questions. |
M|using-superpowers|| "Let me explore the codebase first" | Skills tell you HOW to explore. Check first. |
M|using-superpowers|| "I can check git/files quickly" | Files lack conversation ctx. Check for skills. |
M|using-superpowers|| "Let me gather information first" | Skills tell you HOW to gather information. |
M|using-superpowers|| "This doesn't need a formal skill" | If a skill exists, use it. |
M|using-superpowers|| "I remember this skill" | Skills evolve. Read current version. |
M|using-superpowers|| "This doesn't count as a task" | Action = task. Check for skills. |
M|using-superpowers|| "The skill is overkill" | Simple things become complex. Use it. |
M|using-superpowers|| "I'll just do this one thing first" | Check BEFORE doing anything. |
M|using-superpowers|| "This feels productive" | Undisciplined action wastes time. Skills prevent this. |
M|using-superpowers|| "I know what that means" | Knowing the concept ≠ using the skill. Invoke it. |
M|using-superpowers|When multiple skills could apply, use this order:
M|using-superpowers|1. **Process skills first** (brainstorming, debugging) - these determine HOW to approach the task
M|using-superpowers|2. **Implementation skills second** (frontend-design, mcp-builder) - these guide execution
M|using-superpowers|"Let's build X" → brainstorming first, then implementation skills.
M|using-superpowers|"Fix this bug" → debugging first, then domain-specific skills.
M|using-superpowers|**Rigid** (TDD, debugging): Follow exactly. Don't adapt away discipline.
M|using-superpowers|**Flexible** (patterns): Adapt principles to ctx.
M|using-superpowers|The skill itself tells you which.
M|using-superpowers|Instructions say WHAT, not HOW. "Add X" or "Fix Y" doesn't mean skip workflows.